@NODE "numstr" "Num2Str"

1> num2str 0 ciao bao tsao
"ciao"
1> numstr 10 ciao bao tsao noquote
tsao
1> numstr $VARIABLE "Ciao sono una stringa" "Io una aringa" "Caviale!" Boo
"---???"
It depends on the content of VARIABLE

@ENDNODE

@NODE "reqmx" "RequestMX"

NOTE:
You can think this program could be done better. The GUI is rough (but does all
it has to do) and the texts are highlighted in no way, nor centered. Window
is opened always "there", no control on it (as in RequestSlide). This is
an easy feature, I will add... More, it doesn't care about aspect ratio of
the screen (hm, gadtools doesn't care, too) for radiobuttons, there's no resize
and so on... Hopefully it's bug-free. If there are things you absolutely want,
ask me or do it yourself.

Template:

OPTEXT/A/M,TITLE/K,BT=BODYTOP/K,BB=BODYBOTTOM/K,CHOSEN/K/N,OK/K,CANCEL/K,PUBSCREEN/K

OPTEXT                  here you specify the strings which will be used for
                        mx gadget

TITLE                   the title of the window.

BODYTOP                 a text above the mx. You can use *n to insert newline
                        and so it allows multiline text

BODYBOTTOM              a text under the mx.

CHOSEN                  default choice is 0.

OK                      text for OK gadget (def. "OK")

CANCEL                  text for Cancel gadget (def. "Cancel")

PUBSCREEN               open the window on a public screen. Shouldn't it be
                        put in front of all screens?


A "complex" usage example is provided.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Requi" "Requirements"

  An Amiga(TM) can be useful.

  68020 and AmigaOS 3.0 (v39) are required.

  RequestMX is tested on Amiga1200 with GVP A1291 (EC030+FPU), 4Mb + 2Mb (chip), AmigaOS v39.

@ENDNODE

